## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### Inventory & Classification

Your code has three patterns that break on .NET 8:

| API | Line | Pattern | Problem on .NET 8 |
|-----|-------|---------|--------------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Control flow cleanup | Never thrown — cleanup silently skipped |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue after abort | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop gracefully
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(2000)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in .NET 8.
        }

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool cannot unblock `WaitOne`/`Read`/etc. |
| `while (_running)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Same loop-exit semantic, but token also propagates into called methods |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated `OperationCanceledException`s |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | No abort to reset — just exit the loop after cleanup |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then `Abort()` | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | `Join` blocks until the thread exits *or* timeout; no force-kill needed |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal — the thread checks and responds |

### Critical Pitfall: `GetNextItem()` Must Accept the Token

The original comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." **This is the most important part of the migration.** If it blocks indefinitely, `Cancel()` won't unblock it and `Stop()` will hang. You must thread the token through:

```csharp
// If it blocks on a queue:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // BlockingCollection<T>.Take natively accepts a token
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}

// If it blocks on a WaitHandle/ManualResetEvent:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(
        new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });
    if (index == 1)
        throw new OperationCanceledException(token);
    return DequeueItem();
}

// If it blocks on Thread.Sleep:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000); // cancellable sleep
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

### Common Pitfalls for This Pattern

1. **Cancellation isn't immediate** — it only takes effect at the next checkpoint (`ThrowIfCancellationRequested`, `token.WaitHandle`, or a token-aware API). If `ProcessItem()` is long-running, add checkpoints inside it too.

2. **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** — it's `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. The migrated `Stop()` disposes it.

3. **No force-kill exists in .NET 8** — if the thread truly won't cooperate (e.g., it's stuck in unmanaged code), the only option is to move that work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`.

4. **`finally` blocks now always run** — the original `ResetAbort()` existed to ensure `finally` ran. In .NET 8 with cooperative cancellation, `finally` always runs naturally — no special handling needed.
